{"parse":{"title":"how do you do","pageid":276058,"redirects":[],"wikitext":"==English==\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{l|en|how-do-you-do}}, {{l|en|how-d'ye-do}}, {{l|en|how-de-do}} {{qualifier|noun}}\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{audio|en|En-au-how do you do.ogg|a=AU}}\n\n===Phrase===\n{{en-head|phr|head=?}}\n\n# {{lb|en|formal|dated}} {{ng|A greeting used upon being introduced to someone. Alternatives are [[how are you]], [[pleased to meet you]], and [[nice to meet you]]. (Sometimes used as a rhetorical question among familiar parties, depending on the region).}}\n#* {{RQ:Porter Pollyanna|chapter=8|passage=\"'''How do you do'''?\" began Pollyanna politely. \"I'm from Miss Polly Harrington, and I'd like to see Mrs. Snow, please.\"}}\n\n====Usage notes====\nThis phrase can be inflected: \"I asked him how he was doing\" or (obsolete) \"I asked him how he did\".\n\n====Related terms====\n* {{l|en|how are you doing}} (less formal)\n* {{l|en|howdy}} (informal)\n\n====Translations====\n{{trans-top|Phrase: how do you do}}\n* Abkhaz: {{qualifier|to a woman}} {{t|ab|бышҧаҟоу}}, {{qualifier|to a man}} {{t|ab|ушҧаҟоу}}, {{qualifier|to more than one person}} {{t|ab|шәышҧаҟақоу}}\n* Arabic: {{t|ar|تَشَرَّفْنَا}}\n* Asturian: {{t+|ast|encantáu}} {{qualifier|said by a male}}, {{t+|ast|encantada}} {{qualifier|said by a female}}, {{t|ast|Encantáu de coñocete}}, {{t|ast|¿Cómu tás?}}\n* Catalan: {{t+|ca|encantat|m}}, {{t+|ca|encantada|f}}, {{t|ca|encantat de coneixe't}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Cantonese: {{t|yue|幸會|tr=hang6 wui6}}\n*: Mandarin: {{t+|cmn|幸會|tr=xìnghuì}}, {{t+|cmn|請多關照|tr=qǐng duō guānzhào}}, {{t+|cmn|您好|tr=nínhǎo}}, {{t|cmn|初次見面}}\n* Czech: {{t+|cs|těší mě}}\n* Danish: {{t+|da|goddag}}, {{t|da|(det) glæder mig}}\n* Dutch: {{t|nl|hoe gaat het}}, {{t|nl|hoe gaat het met jou}} {{q|informal}}, {{t|nl|hoe gaat het met u}} {{q|formal}}, {{t|nl|hoe maakt u het}} {{q|formal, dated}}\n* Estonian: {{t|et|kuidas läheb}}\n* Faroese: {{t|fo|hvussu gongur}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|hyvää päivää}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|enchanté|m}}, {{t+|fr|enchantée|f}}\n* Galician: {{t|gl|encantado|m}}\n* German: {{t|de|sehr erfreut}}, {{t|de|sehr angenehm}}, {{t+|de|wie geht es dir}}\n* Greek: {{t+|el|χαίρω πολύ}}\n* Hiligaynon: {{t|hil|kamusta}}\n* Hungarian: {{t+|hu|örvendek}}, {{t+|hu|örvendek a szerencsének}}, {{t+|hu|örülök, hogy megismerhetem}}\n* Indonesian: {{t+|id|apa kabar?}}\n* Italian: {{t|it|piacere di conoscerla|m|f}}, {{t|it|come va}}, {{t|it|tutto bene}}\n* Japanese: {{t+|ja|初めまして|tr=はじめまして, hajimemashite}}, {{qualifier|very formal}} {{t|ja|始めてお目にかかります|tr=はじめておめにかかります, hajimete o-me ni kakarimasu}}, {{t+|ja|御機嫌よう}}, {{t+|ja|ご機嫌よう|tr=ごきげんよう, gokigen yō}}\n* Kazakh: {{t|kk|сәлеметсіз бе}}, {{t|kk|амансыз ба}}\n* Korean: {{t|ko|안녕-하십니까}}\n* Latin: {{t|la|[[quid]] [[agis]]?}} {{qualifier|said to one person}}, {{t|la|[[quid]] [[agitis]]?}} {{qualifier|said to more than one person}}\n* Macedonian: {{t|mk|мило ми е}}, {{t|mk|драго ми е}}\n* Navajo: {{t|nv|nizhónígo ałhééhosiilzįįd}}\n* Norwegian:\n*: Bokmål: formal: {{t|no|gleder meg|lit=I am pleased (to meet you)}}, more informal: {{t|no|hyggelig å møte deg}}, {{t|no|hvordan har du det}}\n* Persian: {{t|fa|از آشنایی شما خوشوقتم|tr=az âšenâyi-ye šomâ xošvaqtam}}\n* Polish: {{t+|pl|jak się masz}} {{qualifier|informal, to a singular listener}}, {{t|pl|jak się macie}} {{qualifier|informal, to many listeners}}, {{t+|pl|jak leci}} {{qualifier|colloquial}}, {{t+|pl|jak tam}} {{qualifier|informal}}, {{t+|pl|co słychać?}}, {{t|pl|miło mi Państwa poznać}} {{q|formally}}\n* Portuguese: {{t|pt|muito prazer}}\n* Russian: {{t|ru|о́чень прия́тно}}, {{t+|ru|как дела́?}}, {{t|ru|прия́тно познако́миться}}\n* Spanish: {{t+|es|encantado}} {{qualifier|said by a male}}, {{t+|es|encantada}} {{qualifier|said by a female}}, {{t|es|¿cómo está usted?}}\n* Swedish: {{t|sv|hur står det till}} {{qualifier|formal}}, {{t|sv|hur är det med dig}} {{qualifier|informal}}\n* Tagalog: {{t+|tl|kumusta}}\n* Tillamook: {{t|til|dəʔ šʔálen̓əxʷš}}\n* Turkish: {{t|tr|nasılsınız}} (formal), {{t|tr|ne var ne yok}} (informal)\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{en-noun}}\n\n# {{lb|en|UK|euphemism}} A [[difficult]] [[situation]]\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1993|author=Nick Park|title=Wallace and Gromit: The Wrong Trousers|passage=Well, this is a fine '''how do you do''' isn't it, Gromit?}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2010|author=Michael Sledge|title=The More I Owe You: A Novel|publisher=Counterpoint Press|isbn=9781582435763|page=78\n|passage=On the winding road to Petropolis, they did not speak, not about modernism or the construction of houses or antique bird jails or fine '''how-do-you-dos'''.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2013|author=Chris Raschka|title=Seriously, Norman!|publisher=Scholastic Inc.|isbn=9780545388467|page=115\n|passage=\"Vienna!\" Mr. B. went on. \"This is a bit of a '''how-do-you-do''', is it not?\"}}\n\n{{cln|en|phrasebook|rhetorical questions|greetings}}"}}